<subSubSection id="56FA71F56B57B5A2259512823058F9B6" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="description">
<paragraph id="1DD97A3AAC6B6BBFB3E90FAB0D047F08" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C3C7B3E18EF42C0AC3BDDA7F5198DE68" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
<emphasis id="B435414A31EBD2EF13970213527117F2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Small tree or shrub</emphasis>
3-5 m high, branches mostly plagiotropic and horizontal (
<emphasis id="0A2A0D20A60DA178FB2CBC5FF33215CD" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Veillon 7138</emphasis>
, P), young stems flexuous, quadrangular or terete, internodes 10-15 mm long (but c. 5 mm long for the flexuous parts); indumentum of young branches and leaves of straight, white, adpressed T-shaped hairs. 
<emphasis id="66B5307DE292348FCF87AE52F204FD5C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Stipules</emphasis>
1-1.5 
<normalizedToken id="302DEA2F6BBB5C941FF09DBDF43AEF6D" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
c. 0.2 mm, narrowly triangular to falciform, pubescent. 
<emphasis id="A2874BB6D24D6400FC95135D6387A194" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Leaves</emphasis>
10.5-11.3 cm long, pinnate, 15-19-foliolate; petiole 10-15 mm long, furrowed, sparsely pubescent; rachis yellowish to light brown, strongly furrowed, non articulated and with thin appressed hairs, thick brown multicellular hairs (colleters) at the leaflets attachments, segments at the leaflets attachments 10-14 mm long; stipels 0.2-0.3 mm long, setiform, early caducous, mostly absent; leaflets opposite, secondary veins visible on both sides of the lamina, upper and lower surfaces with dense, white hairs; terminal leaflet 27-34 
<normalizedToken id="902471252189DC8AF167B86C97A8A52E" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
15-19 mm, ovate to obovate, apex rounded to slightly emarginate, mucronate, base acute, secondary veins 7-12 pairs, lateral leaflets 20-17 
<normalizedToken id="DECA9DAB46163519891C9C6776C6E32E" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
12-14 mm, obovate, apex slightly emarginate, mucronate, secondary veins 6-7 pairs, petiolules 1.2-2 
<normalizedToken id="56D9C0F8DB3CB642302A7111CD09B9C1" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.4-1.5 mm, dark brown on dry specimens, not furrowed. 
<emphasis id="4CC876688EC54CE80999C4062C2B6C0F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Inflorescence</emphasis>
a c. 50 mm long raceme, with more than 40 flowers; peduncle pubescent, quadrangular, c. 10 mm long; pedicel c. 1.5 
<normalizedToken id="A3BF599FBFDC39152E719D9A94E3EBF6" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
0.2 mm. 
<emphasis id="CD70C498136777FEA46AA3AEBD5E994A" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Flower</emphasis>
c. 6.5 mm long; calyx c. 1.5 mm long, campanulate, asymmetrical, 5-lobed, the vexillary (upper) lobes shorter and shallow deltoid, the carinal (lower) lobe longer and acuminate; petals white; standard petal c. 5-6 
<normalizedToken id="C02A1D74C2BCC3EE8EF4F7B9624ACE1B" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4.5 mm wide, obovate, apex slightly emarginate, pubescent outside with apressed T-shaped hairs; wing petals c. 4 
<normalizedToken id="A0286EEC95CB84FB66AF764384DE2373" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.5 mm, slightly shorter than the keel, narrowly obovate to oblong-linear, apex rounded; keel petals 5-5.5 
<normalizedToken id="6489D5EE052F5638E26577C37917C21F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2 mm, obovate, apex rounded, valvately connate along the lower margin halfway to the tip; androecium diadelphous (9 stamens fused and the vexillary one free), staminal tube c. 6 
<normalizedToken id="D5B2E71FDB8DDA7979562F01423DDD4D" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.5 mm; ovary c. 5-ovulate, c. 5 mm long, sessile, glabrous, style c. 2.5 mm long, hook-shaped at apex, stigma capitate. 
<emphasis id="78AF4462614C3564D6327ACBD9D5A558" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Pod</emphasis>
c. 38 
<normalizedToken id="469EC28B9BDCA3C45796C065F73B2272" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3 mm, straight, linear, apex acuminate, indehiscent; valves brown, pubescent with appressed white T-shaped hairs. 
<emphasis id="90A0955287B0C5B0B0DE1661C4201158" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Seeds</emphasis>
5-7, c. 3.5 
<normalizedToken id="AB1491C3B8851B18D2A47D6B47FFE42B" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
5 mm, ellipsoid; testa black.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="120CBA744DAB38607EDDE1D3664BD4DE" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="98B97E9C04166C990EF25D7D0B7625EC" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B2C2F6D7486D62493D10E18C9B880F79" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
<taxonomicName id="0429AA674CD15E0C39C75E25EACAC1A9" authorityName="M. Pignal &amp; L. P. Queiroz" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Indigofera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Indigofera dumbeana" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dumbeana">
<emphasis id="89907A2B9080EF402D26B35F1BA21969" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Indigofera dumbeana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
grows in lowland forests, mostly in wood edges areas (fide 
<emphasis id="2B1B05E30A0A3F8EE8BB29C34DD3AD5E" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Veillon 7138</emphasis>
, P and 
<emphasis id="DD8407B2C5706AD9654096809C703592" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Veillon 7482</emphasis>
, P).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="3C9BE3B84D9E9BA1EBB9838DB4965672" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="418339869F8ADEBC9E001D5972B25D56" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C188286EE119FF547BD7D1563F087C83" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Flowering in March and April, fruiting in May to November.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="CB2FD2CD462C419AD31B535B707F79B9" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="C78079D5D8603E2D05FCFA483D696697" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1CCF4E1E66E2CEF46BB919869DE86C12" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
The specific epithet refers to the 
<normalizedToken id="32663959E366DBB21B8C066E58DB5421" originalValue="Dumbéa">Dumbea</normalizedToken>
River in the mouth of which B. Balansa collected the type material.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="60A2B76062A332790EE90445D128A6E3" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="conservation status">
<paragraph id="05A6486763D9EAABD65B8F63E26A39E8" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Conservation status.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B2B7D43955D51C18E58B270FCAE5FB7C" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
We assessed 
<taxonomicName id="AFFF596F862D72A341AACD1E0D7D62BC" genus="I." lsidName="I. dumbeana" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="dumbeana">
<emphasis id="7567FCAC6D24960592E170D55EC8A48D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">I. dumbeana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as endangered both because it presents small EOO (2358 km2) and AOO (20 km2), and it is located rather in sclerophyllous forests that are perhaps the most endangered formations in New Caledonia, especially at low elevation (
<bibRefCitation id="BFF7B13B47204891AEEA712B8CD976DD" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00058425" author="Bouchet, P" journalOrPublisher="Biodiversity and Conservation" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="415 - 428" refId="B2" refString="Bouchet, P, Jaffre, T, Veillon, JM, 1995. Plant extinction in New Caledonia: Protection of sclerophyll forests urgently needed. Biodiversity and Conservation 4 (4): 415 - 428, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00058425" title="Plant extinction in New Caledonia: Protection of sclerophyll forests urgently needed." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00058425" volume="4" year="1995">Bouchet et al. 1995</bibRefCitation>
). Additionally, this species is known by few and rather old collections which could indicate its rarity in the island.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="ED48E257F791960AE930A4D98A3B3DAE" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="61BEE91AEE460973FA71717860E20CFA" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9B270961C562E457221AF504FFEACADC" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">
We agree with B. Schrire who annotated in 2004 the P00379654 specimen (
<emphasis id="A2DA34C28898280AA9735E0693BFF75F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">M. Debray 2296)</emphasis>
as a new species allied to 
<taxonomicName id="62A273C544A7ED0A48B5AF1C793D1DE3" genus="I." lsidName="I. australis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis id="91B1E8AD7942BBB7F7EF0BBAE411A39C" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">I. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Willd. Specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="C160F48D767CE1ED02EE4D6EF1D7511C" authorityName="M. Pignal &amp; L. P. Queiroz" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Indigofera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Indigofera dumbeana" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dumbeana">
<emphasis id="3249FBEC03025758B0BD565208DF1430" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Indigofera dumbeana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were previously referred to 
<taxonomicName id="6B6A7B9634B45B667800987B829F92F1" genus="I." lsidName="I. australis" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="australis">
<emphasis id="CFA89ED51C940D443F44C0B725CA8607" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">I. australis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="9383E1DEE8514435BECB68845772CA2F" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/00378941.1936.10836355" author="Guillaumin, A" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin de la Societe Botanique de France" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" pagination="294 - 315" refId="B9" refString="Guillaumin, A, 1936. Materiaux pour la flore de la Nouvelle-Caledonie. XL.Revision des Legumineuses. Bulletin de la Societe Botanique de France 83 (4-5): 294 - 315, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/00378941.1936.10836355" title="Materiaux pour la flore de la Nouvelle-Caledonie. XL. Revision des Legumineuses." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/00378941.1936.10836355" volume="83" year="1936">Guillaumin (1936)</bibRefCitation>
. These species are clearly rendered distinct by the habit as 
<taxonomicName id="B74AED9BB338854752312EC5EFA7EC83" genus="I." lsidName="I. dumbeana" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="dumbeana">
<emphasis id="8F811EEEC8A712D7CB7DFB5376B60CDF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">I. dumbeana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
presents plagiotropical, almost horizontal branches, stipules triangular or asymmetrical and falciform (vs. linear), and flowers with a five lobate calyx and white petals (vs. flowers with a truncate calyx and pink to purple petals). 
<taxonomicName id="D9AE3204D1ADDF45DCEB915714F9B725" authorityName="M. Pignal &amp; L. P. Queiroz" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Indigofera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Indigofera dumbeana" order="Fabales" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dumbeana">
<emphasis id="F8F6B111B528495E7B6F054B6A898C4B" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">Indigofera dumbeana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more similar to 
<taxonomicName id="67D6F4E380E01CF7770729CB9821533C" genus="I." lsidName="I. zollingeriana" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="zollingeriana">
<emphasis id="AA95ED72E026D3E77A7399B9CF39260D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">I. zollingeriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, both occurring as a tall shrub or small tree habit with plagiotropical branches, but they are clearly distinct by the fruit straight with rectangular seeds linearly arranged (vs. fruit sinuous with transversely compressed seeds arranged like a stack of coins in 
<taxonomicName id="AB3DFF3DE49923E60D5BAE68F54D6320" genus="I." lsidName="I. zollingeriana" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" rank="species" species="zollingeriana">
<emphasis id="F6A2BF723A2CAFF4161FBECE1EE155AA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="53">I. zollingeriana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Additionally, they present important differences in leaf and flower traits as presented in Table 
<tableCitation id="A8D417A58B325C89DE591A579310B378" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="T1" captionText="Table 1. Comparison between the new species of Indigofera from New Caledonia with the Australian I. australis and the widespread species I. zollingeriana." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/BCC99796AD403A8E35F604C08E809DA3" pageId="0" pageNumber="53" tableUuid="BCC99796AD403A8E35F604C08E809DA3">1</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
